{{Geo-term-stub}}

{{Jurassic}} In the [[geologic timescale]], the '''Sinemurian''' is an [[age (geology)|age]] and [[stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] in the [[Early Jurassic|Early or Lower Jurassic]] [[epoch (geology)|epoch]] or [[series (stratigraphy)|series]]. It spans the time between 199.3 ¬± 2 [[annum|Ma]] and 190.8 ¬± 1.5 Ma (million years ago).<ref name="benton, 2012">{{cite book|last=Benton|first=Michael J.|title=Prehistoric Life|year=2012|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=Edinburgh, Scotland|isbn=978-0-7566-9910-9|pages=44‚Äì45}}</ref> The Sinemurian is preceded by the [[Hettangian]] and is followed by the [[Pliensbachian]].<ref>For a detailed geologic timescale see Gradstein ''et al.'' (2004)</ref>
In Europe the Sinemurian age, together with the Hettangian age, saw the deposition of the lower [[Lias Group|Lias]], in Great Britain known as the [[Blue Lias]].
==Stratigraphic definitions== [[Image:Cliff Face East Quantoxhead - geograph.org.uk - 1003272.jpg|thumb|Jurassic rock strata in the cliffs at [[East Quantoxhead]], near the Sinemurian [[List of Global Boundary Stratotype Sections and Points|golden spike]].]] The Sinemurian stage was defined and introduced into scientific literature by French palaeontologist [[Alcide d'Orbigny]] in 1842. It takes its name from the French town of [[Semur-en-Auxois]], near [[Dijon]]. The [[calcareous]] soil formed from the Jurassic [[limestone]] of the region is in part responsible for the character of the classic [[Sancerre (wine)|Sancerre wines]].
The base of the Sinemurian stage is at the first appearance of the [[ammonite]] [[genus|genera]] ''[[Vermiceras]]'' and ''[[Metophioceras]]'' in the stratigraphic record. A global reference profile ([[GSSP|GSSP or golden spike]]) for the Sinemurian stage is located in a cliff north of the hamlet of [[East Quantoxhead]], 6 kilometres east of [[Watchet]], [[Somerset]], [[England]].<ref>See for the description of the GSSP Bloos & Page (2001)</ref> [[File:Eteoderoceras armatum sinemurian.jpg|thumb|left|''Eteoderoceras armatum'', a Sinemurian ammonite]] The top of the Sinemurian (the base of the Pliensbachian) is at the first appearances of the ammonite species ''[[Bifericeras|Bifericeras donovani]]'' and ammonite genus ''[[Apoderoceras]]''.
The Sinemurian contains six ammonite [[biozone]]s in the [[Tethys Ocean|Tethys domain]]: *zone of ''[[Echioceras|Echioceras raricostatum]]'' *zone of ''[[Oxynotoceras|Oxynotoceras oxynotum]]'' *zone of ''[[Caenisites|Caenisites turneri]]'' *zone of ''[[Arnioceras|Arnioceras semicostatum]]'' *zone of ''[[Arietites|Arietites bucklandi]]''
